<doc id="1198015" wikidata="Q516994" url="?curid=1198015" title="Decisional Diffie–Hellman assumption">
<text>The decisional Diffie–Hellman (DDH) assumption is a computational hardness assumption about a certain problem involving discrete logarithms in cyclic groups. It is used as the basis to prove the security of many cryptographic protocols, most notably the ElGamal and Cramer–Shoup cryptosystems.

==Definition==

Consider a (multiplicative) cyclic group formula_1 of order formula_2, and with generator formula_3. The DDH assumption states that, given formula_4 and formula_5 for uniformly and independently chosen formula_6, the value formula_7 &quot;looks like&quot; a random element in formula_1.

This intuitive notion can be formally stated by saying that the following two probability distributions are computationally indistinguishable (in the security parameter, formula_9):
* formula_10, where formula_11 and formula_12 are randomly and independently chosen from formula_13.
* formula_14, where formula_15 are randomly and independently chosen from formula_13.

Triples of the first kind are often called DDH triplet or DDH tuples.

==Relation to other assumptions==

The DDH assumption is related to the discrete log assumption. If it were possible to efficiently compute discrete logs in formula_1, then the DDH assumption would not hold in formula_1. Given formula_19, one could efficiently decide whether formula_20 by first taking the discrete formula_21 of formula_4, and then comparing formula_23 with formula_24.

DDH is considered to be a stronger assumption than the discrete logarithm assumption, because there are groups for which computing discrete logs is believed to be hard (And thus the DL Assumption is believed to be true), but detecting DDH tuples is easy (And thus DDH is false). Because of this, requiring that the DDH assumption holds in a group is believed to be a more restrictive requirement than DL.

The DDH assumption is also related to the computational Diffie–Hellman assumption (CDH). If it were possible to efficiently compute formula_7 from formula_26, then one could easily distinguish the two probability distributions above. DDH is considered to be a stronger assumption than CDH because if CDH is solved, which means we can get formula_7, the answer to DDH will become obvious.

==Other properties==

The problem of detecting DDH tuples is random self-reducible, meaning, roughly, that if it is hard for even a small fraction of inputs, it is hard for almost all inputs; if it is easy for even a small fraction of inputs, it is easy for almost all inputs.

==Groups for which DDH is assumed to hold==

When using a cryptographic protocol whose security depends on the DDH assumption, it is important that the protocol is implemented using groups where DDH is believed to hold:

* The subgroup formula_28 of formula_29-th residues modulo a prime formula_30, where formula_2 is also a large prime (also called a Schnorr group). For the case of formula_32, this corresponds to the group of quadratic residues modulo a safe prime.
* The quotient group formula_33 for a safe prime formula_34, which consists of the cosets formula_35. These cosets formula_36 can be represented by formula_37, which implies formula_38. Since formula_33 and formula_28 are isomorphic, and the isomorphism can be computed efficiently in both direction, DDH is equally hard in both groups.
* A prime-order elliptic curve formula_41 over the field formula_42, where formula_43 is prime, provided formula_41 has large embedding degree.
* A Jacobian of a hyper-elliptic curve over the field formula_42 with a prime number of reduced divisors, where formula_43 is prime, provided the Jacobian has large embedding degree.

Importantly, the DDH assumption does not hold in the multiplicative group formula_47, where formula_43 is prime. This is because if formula_3 is a generator of formula_47, then the Legendre symbol of formula_4 reveals if formula_11 is even or odd. Given formula_4, formula_5 and formula_7, one can thus efficiently compute and compare the least significant bit of formula_11, formula_12 and formula_58, respectively, which provides a probabilistic method to distinguish formula_7 from a random group element.

The DDH assumption does not hold on elliptic curves over formula_42 with small embedding degree (say, less than formula_61), a class which includes supersingular elliptic curves. This is because the Weil pairing or Tate pairing can be used to solve the problem directly as follows: given formula_62 on such a curve, one can compute formula_63 and formula_64. By the bilinearity of the pairings, the two expressions are equal if and only if formula_65 modulo the order of formula_66. If the embedding degree is large (say around the size of formula_43) then the DDH assumption will still hold because the pairing cannot be computed. Even if the embedding degree is small, there are some subgroups of the curve in which the DDH assumption is believed to hold.

