<doc id="1198268" wikidata="Q7631153" url="?curid=1198268" title="Subgroup growth">
<text>In mathematics, subgroup growth is a branch of group theory, dealing with quantitative questions about subgroups of a given group.

Let formula_1 be a finitely generated group. Then, for each integer formula_2 define formula_3 to be the number of subgroups formula_4 of index formula_2 in formula_1. Similarly, if formula_1 is a topological group, formula_8 denotes the number of open subgroups formula_9 of index formula_2 in formula_1. One similarly defines formula_12 and formula_13 to denote the number of maximal and normal subgroups of index formula_2, respectively.

Subgroup growth studies these functions, their interplay, and the characterization of group theoretical properties in terms of these functions.

The theory was motivated by the desire to enumerate finite groups of given order, and the analogy with Mikhail Gromov&#x27;s notion of word growth.

==Nilpotent groups==
Let formula_15 be a finitely generated torsionfree nilpotent group. Then there exists a composition series with infinite cyclic factors, which induces a bijection (though not necessarily a homomorphism).

:formula_16

such that group multiplication can be expressed by polynomial functions in these coordinates; in particular, the multiplication is definable. Using methods from the model theory of p-adic integers, F. Grunewald, D. Segal and G. Smith showed that the local zeta function
:formula_17
is a rational function in formula_18.

As an example, let formula_19 be the discrete Heisenberg group. This group has a &quot;presentation&quot; with generators formula_20 and relations
:formula_21
